Here’s a simple way to picture a diagonal slice through a cube.

Imagine a cube like this:

      +--------+
     /|       /|
    / |      / |
   +--------+  |
   |  |     |  |
   |  +-----|--+
   | /      | /
   |/       |/
   +--------+

Now picture a plane cutting through it at an angle, not straight up-down and not flat. Something like this:

      +--------+
     /|    __ /|
    / | __/  / |
   +--/-----+  |
   | / \    |  |
   |/___\___|--+
   | \   /  | /
   |  \_/   |/
   +--------+

That angled cut can produce different shapes depending on the exact angle:
	•	a rectangle
	•	a parallelogram
	•	a hexagon

A classic “diagonal slice through the middle” is often shown as a hexagon.

More explicitly:

       ______
     /      \
    /        \
    \        /
     \______/

That hexagon is the cross-section you’d see if the cube were cut by the right diagonal plane.

The reason your earlier “cake slices” answer missed it is that a slice through a 3D object creates a 2D shape at the cut surface, not just multiple chunks.

Quick intuition

A cube has 6 faces.
A diagonal plane can intersect several of them at once.
When it hits 6 edges, the cross-section is a hexagon.

Salience Engine / Dial

Here’s a clean version you can use.

Salience Engine v1.0

Purpose:
Increase the chance that an idea, message, product, or experience feels meaningful, memorable, and action-driving.

Core formula

Salience = Attention × Emotion × Meaning × Contrast × Embodiment

If one is near zero, the experience usually won’t stick.

The five dials

1. Attention

How strongly it captures focus.

Increase with:
	•	novelty
	•	clarity
	•	specificity
	•	interruption of expectation

Low attention = ignored.

2. Emotion

How much felt charge it carries.

Increase with:
	•	awe
	•	urgency
	•	desire
	•	fear
	•	pride
	•	relief

Low emotion = forgotten.

3. Meaning

How much it connects to identity, purpose, or worldview.

Increase with:
	•	“this is about me”
	•	“this explains something”
	•	“this matters”
	•	symbolic framing

Low meaning = interesting but empty.

4. Contrast

How sharply it differs from background.

Increase with:
	•	before/after
	•	break/resolve
	•	silence/hit
	•	ordinary/unexpected

Low contrast = flat.

5. Embodiment

How much it enters the body, not just the mind.

Increase with:
	•	rhythm
	•	pacing
	•	visual form
	•	physical action
	•	repetition
	•	breath / cadence

Low embodiment = understood but not felt.

⸻

Dial version

Rate each from 1–10:

Attention   [1---10]
Emotion     [1---10]
Meaning     [1---10]
Contrast    [1---10]
Embodiment  [1---10]

Then ask:
	•	Which dial is weakest?
	•	Which dial can be raised without making the whole thing corny or manipulative?

Output bands

0–15 total

Background noise

16–25

Interesting but forgettable

26–35

Sticky

36–45

Memorable / persuasive

46–50

Peak salience

⸻

Trigger sequence

Use this order:

1. Hook

Grab attention.

2. Pattern

Give the brain something to track.

3. Break

Violate expectation.

4. Resolve

Provide coherence.

5. Anchor

Tie it to identity, action, or memory.

That sequence is what makes something feel like it “landed.”

⸻

Example: Gluteform

Weak version

“A seat cushion that supports posture.”

Scores:
	•	Attention: 3
	•	Emotion: 2
	•	Meaning: 3
	•	Contrast: 2
	•	Embodiment: 4

Forgettable.

Stronger version

“The gym tool you use all day. Gluteform helps fight flat-seat posture, supports your hips, and turns desk time into active shaping time.”

Scores:
	•	Attention: 7
	•	Emotion: 6
	•	Meaning: 7
	•	Contrast: 6
	•	Embodiment: 8

Much stickier.

⸻

Safety rule

High salience is powerful, so use this constraint:

No salience without truth anchor.
No emotional amplification without reality check.
No identity hook without opt-out.

That keeps it persuasive without becoming manipulative.

